@pipermerriam yes, that's right. Seems it got lost in that refactoring. 

@glaksmono 
The message is only inside the exception now but it still needs to be printed to the user.

I'd suggest keeping the original logic from the Go code in the version 3 case here:

	case byte(Version3):
		if len(caveat) < version3CaveatMinLen {
			// If it has the version 3 caveat tag and it's too short, it's
			// almost certainly an id, not an encrypted payload.
			return nil, errgo.Newf("caveat id payload not provided for caveat id %q", caveat)
		}

Our base store is now proper Redux, paired with [redux-observable](https://github.com/redux-observable/redux-observable). The way to [cancel async actions](https://github.com/redux-observable/redux-observable#cancellation) is through other actions:

```js
dispatch(
  (actions) => Observable.timer(1000)
    .map(() => ({ type: 'TIMER_COMPLETE'}))
    .takeUntil(
      actions.ofType('ABORT_TIMER')
    )
    // `actions.ofType('ABORT_TIMER')` is equivalent to
    // `actions.filter(action => action.type === 'ABORT_TIMER')`
);

// elsewhere in your code you can abort with a simple dispatch
dispatch({ type: 'ABORT_TIMER' });
```

You're absolutely right about using `subscriber.next({ type: 'ABORT_EXECUTION', id })` here. I'll have to update and rebase this PR.

But we still need to catch the TypeError, right? Then it doesn't look better than before.

```py
if value:
  try:
    return address_decoder(value)
  except TypeError:
    self.fail('Please specify a valid hex-encoded address.')
self.fail('Please specify a valid hex-encoded address.')
```
